	                <h1>
    	                <span id="Template_NewsDate1_lblDate" style="float:right"></span>

	                    Strike Action 30th November 2011


	                    <span id="Template_ctl08_lblMessage"><font color="Red"></font></span>

	                </h1>
                	
<p class="ImmTextAlign_Left">On 30<sup>th</sup> November 2011, the
Scottish Trades Union Congress (STUC) has called for a day of
&lsquo;strike action&rsquo; in order to protect public service pensions. This
will involve a significant gathering and procession in Edinburgh
City Centre as well as smaller protests/pickets around the
Force.<br />
<br />
The Edinburgh procession will commence at 12pm from Johnston
Terrace and will travel down the Royal Mile. Following a rally, at
the front of the Scottish Parliament, the event will conclude
around 2pm. The organisers expect the event to attract up to 3,000
people, the vast majority of whom will be there for peaceful
protest.&nbsp; Lothian and Borders Police will play a vital role in
enabling this peaceful protest whilst minimising disruption to the
local community and ensuring public safety.<br />
<br />
I would like to take this opportunity to reassure people within the
City and other parts of the Force that we have undertaken a
significant amount of planning for this event and we are fully
prepared. We have worked closely with various partner agencies and
trade unions to both facilitate and mitigate the impact of this
industrial action.<br />
<br />
The Police operation will be conducted with the aim of upholding
the law, maintaining order and protecting life and property in
order to:</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<ul>
<li>Facilitate the rights of freedom of assembly and association
and freedom of speech;</li>
<li class="MsoNormal">Ensure that public order and public safety is
maintained;</li>
<li class="MsoNormal">Provide public reassurance and maintain
community confidence;</li>
<li class="MsoNormal">Ensure business continuity within Lothian and
Borders Police is maintained;</li>
<li class="MsoNormal">Minimise disruption to the people and traffic
within the City of Edinburgh and elsewhere, enabling day to day
business to continue and a return to normality to be achieved as
soon as reasonably practicable;</li>
<li class="MsoNormal">Provide an appropriate and proportionate
response to any anti social behaviour and criminal activity,
bringing offenders to justice during or after the event;</li>
<li class="MsoNormal">Enhance the reputation of the Scottish Police
Service and work within the principles of efficiency and health and
safety;</li>
<li class="MsoBodyText2">Prevent crime and disorder and secure
evidence to prosecute those who engage in crime and disorder.</li>
</ul>
<p class="MsoBodyText2">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">At this stage, there is no information to
indicate that this event will be anything other than peaceful.
Businesses should however be aware that some protesters may well
attend at certain premises in order to air grievances. We would ask
that you make us aware of any such incidents as soon as possible to
enable us to respond if necessary.<br />
<br />
Lothian and Borders Police is proud of the strong links we have
with our communities and in the build up to this event, local
officers will be communicating with businesses and community groups
in order to pass on any relevant information and alleviate any
concerns. I would urge you to work with us to ensure that this
event passes safely and I appreciate your assistance in this
matter.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Iain Livingstone</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Assistant Chief Constable</p>
<p>Lothian and Borders Police</p>
